This paper is about learning Bayesian networks from data, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of machine learning. The minimum description length (MDL) principle is a popular method for learning Bayesian networks, which suggests that the paper could be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the sample complexity of MDL-based learning procedures, which involves analyzing the number of samples needed to learn an epsilon-close approximation with confidence delta. This suggests that the paper could also be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the complexity of the target distribution and proposes a method for speeding up the learning process, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
